<paragraph blockId="20.[151,1127,219,1140]" pageId="20" pageNumber="249">
<keyLead pageId="20" pageNumber="249">
4(3) Antennal pedicel with blackish spot on outer side extended laterally up to ventral margin (
<figureCitation box="[303,369,635,659]" captionStart="Figs 3–5" captionStartId="7.[113,150,1510,1529]" captionTargetBox="[138,1063,219,1453]" captionTargetId="figure-13@7.[138,1065,219,1454]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figs 3–5. Periscelis species. 3 – Periscelis (P.) fugax sp. nov., male paratype, body dorsally, length ca 3.0 mm (Czech Republic: S. Moravia); 4 – same specimen, laterally; 5 – Periscelis (P.) winnertzii Egger, 1862, male, head and thorax subdorsally, body length ca 4.1 mm (Hungary). Photo by J. Roháček." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5378013" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5378013/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="249">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
). Mesonotum medially unicolorous grey (
<figureCitation box="[824,889,635,659]" captionStart="Figs 3–5" captionStartId="7.[113,150,1510,1529]" captionTargetBox="[138,1063,219,1453]" captionTargetId="figure-13@7.[138,1065,219,1454]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figs 3–5. Periscelis species. 3 – Periscelis (P.) fugax sp. nov., male paratype, body dorsally, length ca 3.0 mm (Czech Republic: S. Moravia); 4 – same specimen, laterally; 5 – Periscelis (P.) winnertzii Egger, 1862, male, head and thorax subdorsally, body length ca 4.1 mm (Hungary). Photo by J. Roháček." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5378013" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5378013/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="249">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
) or with brown vittae only indicated (
<figureCitation box="[381,462,667,692]" captionStart="Figs 33–34" captionStartId="18.[151,188,1297,1316]" captionTargetBox="[189,1089,219,1287]" captionTargetId="figure-10@18.[189,1089,219,1287]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="Figs 33–34. Periscelis (P.) winnertzii Egger, 1862, female (Slovakia), body length ca 4.2 mm. 33 – living adult, laterally; 34 – same specimen, dorsally. Photo by J. Roháček." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5378025" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5378025/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="249">Fig. 33</figureCitation>
); scutellum all dark or with yellow restricted to apex (
<figureCitation box="[1051,1122,667,691]" captionStart="Figs 3–5" captionStartId="7.[113,150,1510,1529]" captionTargetBox="[138,1063,219,1453]" captionTargetId="figure-13@7.[138,1065,219,1454]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figs 3–5. Periscelis species. 3 – Periscelis (P.) fugax sp. nov., male paratype, body dorsally, length ca 3.0 mm (Czech Republic: S. Moravia); 4 – same specimen, laterally; 5 – Periscelis (P.) winnertzii Egger, 1862, male, head and thorax subdorsally, body length ca 4.1 mm (Hungary). Photo by J. Roháček." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5378013" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5378013/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="249">Figs 5</figureCitation>
